Here is a basic program that reads a text file line by line, counts the number of appearances of each word in the text file, and prints the results to the console:
C++ code:
```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <fstream>
#include <map>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ifstream fin("input_file.txt"); // Open the input file
    map<string, int> countMap; // Map to store word counts
    string line; // Line to read from the input file
    while (getline(fin, line)) { // Loop through each line in the input file
        for (int i = 0; i < line.length(); i++) { // Count appearances of each character in the line
            if (isalpha(line[i])) { // Only count characters in the alphabet (A-Z and a-z)
                if (countMap.find(line[i]) == countMap.end()) { // If the character has not been seen before, add it to the map and increment its counter
                    countMap[line[i]] = 1;
                } else { // Otherwise, increment its counter by 1
                    countMap[line[i]]++;
                }
            }
        } // For each character in the line, increment its counter in the map if it has not been seen before
        cout << countMap["the"] << endl; // Print the word "the" with its corresponding count from the map to the console
        for (auto iter = countMap.begin(); iter != countMap.end(); iter++) { // Print all words and their counts to the console
            cout << iter->first << ":" << iter->second << endl;
        }
    }// For each line in the input file, print its word count to the console
}// Program execution terminates here

Γράψτε ένα πρόγραμμα για να βρείτε τον n-οστό αριθμό Fibonacci χρησιμοποιώντας δυναμικό προγραμματισμό.

```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int fib(int n) {
    int fib_val = 0;
    if (n == 0 || n == 1) return fib_val;
    else {
        fib_val = fib(n - 1) + fib(n - 2);
        return fib_val;
    }
}
```

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>
#include <limits>
#include <algorithm>
using namespace std;
int fib(int n) {
    if (n == 0 || n == 1) return n;
    else {
        int a = n - 1; // a is the current index to be tested for ending recursion. If it's the first time through, a is the first element of the array. Otherwise, a is the next element of the array to be tested. In any case, it's a is the current index. Thus, a will always be less than or equal to n. We use this fact to terminate the recursion and compute the Fibonacci sequence without any additional checking. If you're curious about why we have this check, imagine if we had code like this: for (int i = n; i > 1; i--) doStuff(); That would cause an infinite loop because if you have i > 1 in the beginning of the loop, you'll never get i less than or equal to one, so you'll never get out of the loop! Thus, to avoid this problem, we check if a is less than or equal to n before we even start the loop! It's always true in this case since we can only test for a < n when a is less than or equal to n. So in summary, this check ensures that we won't ever get into an infinite loop and will only ever recurse for as long as necessary! In fact, this is exactly what happens with recursive algorithms like Fibonacci! This check prevents us from ever trying to compute an element of the Fibonacci sequence more than once! This ensures that our algorithm will only ever need to recurse as many times as it needs to in order to find all of the elements of the Fibonacci sequence! Also note that there's no reason why you couldn't use a while loop instead of a for loop here. The only difference between them is how they handle infinite loops: while loops break out of loops when they encounter an error condition (such as reaching a break statement), while for loops terminate when they encounter a break statement or hit their end condition (which would happen if they reached their maximum iteration count).

